# WHAT IT IS
#   Modbus is the de-facto industrial automation protocol that
#   has been the standard inter-PLC + PLC-to-HMI communication
#   protocol since 1979.  It comes in two flavors:
#
#     • **Modbus RTU** — frames over RS-485 / RS-232 / RS-422
#       serial transport with strict 3.5-character-time inter-
#       frame silence requirements and per-frame CRC-16
#       checksum.  Half-duplex bus topology: one master, up to
#       247 slaves identified by 8-bit address.
#
#     • **Modbus TCP** (a.k.a. **Modbus/TCP** or "Modbus
#       Messaging on TCP/IP", IETF RFC's "Open Modbus
#       Specification") — frames the same PDU but wraps it in
#       a 7-byte MBAP (Modbus Application Header) prefix
#       containing a 16-bit transaction-ID for request/
#       response matching, a 16-bit protocol identifier
#       (always 0 for Modbus/TCP), a 16-bit length field, and
#       a 1-byte unit identifier.  Runs over a regular TCP
#       connection on port 502 by default.
#
#   Many industrial PLCs (Schneider Modicon, Siemens S7
#   CommunicationProcessor, ABB AC500, Eaton ELC, Wago 750-880,
#   IDEC FT1A, Bosch Rexroth IndraControl) limit incoming Modbus
#   TCP connections to ONE concurrent client.  Or the upstream
#   device is a serial-only Modbus RTU device that you want to
#   expose to multiple Modbus TCP-only HMIs / SCADAs /
#   analytics-pipelines simultaneously.
#
#   `modbus_proxy` solves both cases:
#
#     • In **TCP-upstream mode** (`modbus_proxy tcp <SERVER>`):
#       opens a single persistent TCP connection to the
#       upstream PLC's Modbus TCP server, then serves multiple
#       concurrent downstream TCP clients on `--proxy-port`.
#       Each client request is queued with its original
#       transaction-ID, forwarded to the upstream PLC in
#       serialized order with the configured `--request-delay`
#       inter-frame gap, and the response is routed back to
#       the originating client based on the MBAP transaction-
#       ID.
#
#     • In **RTU-upstream mode** (`modbus_proxy rtu <SERIAL>`):
#       opens a single serial port to the RS-485 Modbus RTU
#       bus, transcodes incoming Modbus TCP MBAP frames to
#       Modbus RTU PDU frames (stripping the MBAP header,
#       appending the CRC-16), waits the calculated 3.5-
#       character-time inter-frame silence, sends the frame,
#       reads the RTU response, transcodes back to MBAP, and
#       returns it to the originating TCP client.
#
#   Optional systemd integration (compile with the `systemd`
#   feature):  notifies systemd of readiness on the
#   `sd_notify(READY=1)` channel, sends watchdog keepalives,
#   and runs cleanly under a systemd `Type=notify` service
#   unit.
#
